In Need for Speed: The Run races across America.
Reviews
Originally a carefree ride turns into a routine morning shift due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes.
Although the ambition was largely achieved, it is not valid when no one apparently wanted to do anything else.
The new episode with the subtitle The Run woke up before the release of high expectations.
He promised that the years of the Need for Speed racing series would move again a bit in a new direction, and from playable demonstrations he appeared as a game that would not be in the genre of action racing only to number.
We were also curious about how the inserted passages will turn out, in which the main hero gets out of the car and takes place in his own way.
But, as the NFS series tends to be, many are in turn a little different from what we expected.
They are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole drags down a few unnecessary mistakes that have appeared in the series for more or less several years.
So it's not really a mistake, but rather an incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced to a story whose main hero Jack has certain problems of a personal nature and as a solution he offers to participate in an illegal race across America.
You get behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco and your job is to arrive first in New York.
The idea carries some interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
One doesn't feel like the game is always the same.
Some of the environments are also very nice to see, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing world-class.
But driving across the desert, the autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains seems visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are made from time to time by some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught in a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to be covered in an avalanche.
In addition, individual races are quite well placed behind each other.
There are only a few types, but it's enough.
For a while you try to overtake the required number of opponents (the basically classic race), then you catch up with time (classical fight with stopwatch) and then you have a duel with a single opponent.
From time to time, police will also get involved, which makes your efforts even more unpleasant.
The novelty is the passages outside the car.
It's more like an interactive animation where Jack is mostly fleeing from someone, and you have to help him do it by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
It's nothing complicated.
It surprises, however, that these passages are much less in play than you would expect (perhaps even three).
In the end, however, it is for the benefit of the matter, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and thus, in the context of the above mentioned, it ranks among the elements that make the game better.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that it is definitely not who knows what nowadays, but it is not to be said that it is a negative.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will have to look elsewhere.
But the action-based racing of the local driving model still works quite well, even though we could find a better one in competition.
So far, everything is perfectly fine.
However, problems begin to appear after some time.
Unlike the model, the collision model is no longer in order.
We don't expect this type of game to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but when virtually no impact on any object you have any idea how your car will behave, then perhaps everything is not quite right.
Typically, when you cross or pass cars in normal traffic, sometimes you just lightly lick each other, but sometimes in an almost identical situation your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even smash right in.
The rebooting system doesn't really matter, but it's gonna make you feel really upset.
Reboots are designed so that if you smash or go far off track, the game will throw you back to the last clue point on the track.
But only five reboots are available in each race.
When you're exhausted, you have to start the race all over again.
So it's more of a tool in case something goes wrong than you can rely on them explicitly.
But sometimes reboots don't help, they solve them only when they have to learn a given section of the race by heart.
The big problem of the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some corners, for example, need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply can't fit into them.
Other times, you will meet "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive there first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is particularly upsetting in situations where you can see how between the two opposite cars the opponent will easily pass in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
It doesn't matter when you get to them because it's "counted" so that the situation always happens just before your nose.
Competitors have another advantage.
During the whole time playing you will find several places where you, no matter the time again, always overtake the same opponent in the same place.
It hits most at the end of the game on a long bridge where you're going in the opposite direction.
The opponent has to get there in front of you at all costs, apparently.
When he's ahead of you, he's making it harder for you to see the cars going against you, so at first, you're probably going to smash around a couple of times.
You can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-y, but the design is so obvious that it will reliably disgust you quickly.
And it's a shame, because despite a simple driving model, playing is fun and sometimes even so action that sometimes you literally can't watch where you fly.
And it doesn't really matter whether the concept of 50 unique tracks, races so that boredom doesn't stand a chance or anything else.
An unconventional idea is to change cars during races.
You have to pay attention to the gas stations at the roads, because that's where you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you can handle what you just have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American cars on straight highways and exotic supersports on technical rides, such as winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand with the mode of challenges, which are races in individual locations that you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points into your profile, which is common to both challenges and stories.
Different objects are unlocked for higher levels of the driver: starting with cars and ending with backgrounds for the profile.
It is also connected again with the Autolog online feature, which inter alia compares your achieved results with other players and provides other community functions.
One of the other hard to understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
With your car you can get to the subway tunnel (either) where you drive it in the dark on the tracks (so be it).
The speedometer flashes numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (either) and the subway set comes from behind and uncompromisingly scrapes you off.
In the newsroom, we will probably have a few more days to discuss whether no one really thought about making the game, or whether the authors think we are really such big jerks.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in several cases even great.
It is so saddened that in some of the more intense moments the scans fall, and in some cases it is quite tragic.
However, this is mainly about car crashes with more participants, where you would no longer be able to get a smooth shot.
The soundtrack is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest possible range of younger audiences, soundtrack from the category "every dog in a different village" was created, but it can be assumed that because of listening to music someone will probably not buy the game.
The overall impression from Need for Speed: The Run is so greatly embarrassed.
If the game were to avoid completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run has been the best piece of NFS in the last few years.
But this is how the game is unfinished.
I'm sure it's fun, but get ready for your mistakes to smash into your eyes with airport spotlights.
