How tour prices developed since 1989
By 1989 only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia at the time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time only sold tours to socialist bloc countries in the vast majority, as travel to the west was very limited.
The Czech tourists thus travelled to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi na Crimea u Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was also possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the Czech tourists' journeys to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialism era was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely individually even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, for example, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at that time, but it was necessary to stand the line overnight with a sleeping bag or to have a "good friend" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without the foreign exchange promise it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) to travel to the West.
Most often, however, the Czechs spent their holidays in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages, which the Czechs bought and survives today.
The Czechs' travel has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we no longer realize today is that it was not possible to travel freely to our most popular Croatia by 1989, as it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s, visa requirements were lifted to neighbouring Western European countries, which started a huge wave of short-term visits mainly to Austria's Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't get enough trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to take a look at it for a while.
In Paris, for example, Czech tours slept in tents in parks, as our incomes did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a guest house.
A typical feature of Czech traveling at this time was driving your own food, canned goods, salamis, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely exchangeable Czech koruna, which allowed our tourists to buy Western currency freely after many decades.
However, our standard of living and with it average wages were rising, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Due to increased demand for travel, travel agencies have regularly started preparing charter air services tours since 1997, making air tours more incredibly cheaper than in the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantitative discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs had visa-free contact with virtually all developed countries in the world, except the US, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of Puerto Revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when due to considerable demand it was delivered from the Czech Republic historically the first direct charter flight to exoticity, it was to Thailand.
From this year onwards, direct charters fly with Czech tourists to warm faraway countries every year, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visiting around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and thus our country has definitely become one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) for the first time in history and spent more than CZK 15,000 per person on one foreign holiday, including on the site.
