A personal massacre
Emotionally strong new book by Peter Englund called Beauty and Grief: The Secret History of World War I (The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War) begins with such a long list of performers that you will get dizzy.
One piece of advice on how to act at that moment: Pluck this page carefully and make a bookmark out of it.
You will get to know all the people in the novel story of Mr Englund very well, and this list will serve you as a navigation - a kind of beacon - at times when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in various situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it quite correctly, as "an antihistorical work."
It contains several very well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, on the contrary, almost missing ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates on tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, it explains the author, as it explains "a book about what it was like," mainly "feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods."
"Beauty and grief" combines the war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go crazy or die.
Their lives are flickering like flames of candlelight burning in a church - new ones are added to the tangle of fates while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from classical historical novels.
It alters the idea that World War I was just about the terrifying trenches on the Western front.
The "beautiful and sorrowful" is skilled in exploring other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with bee nests falling on them, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids or facing the presence of flies tse-tse.
Almost from the beginning, this is a very touching reading.
War consumes people's lives like some kind of natural disaster, like hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When gunfire starts in the distance and you're the woman who's at home with her kids, will you run away or stay?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the entire war was unleashed.
"The vacuum resulting from the lack of facts," noted Mr Englund, "was filled with conjecture, conjecture, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors. "
"Beautiful and sad" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are generally taken from CVs, letters and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound scary and intriguing, but the inclusion of tiny moments and details makes them absolutely alive and believable.
Many of them discuss suffering and dealing with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says: "Substitutes everywhere, substitutes everywhere. "
"Coffee substitute, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It refers to "meat produced from pressed rice cooked in mutton fat (and supplemented with a false bone of wood), dried roots tobacco and dried potato husks, shoes with wooden soles'.
It mentions that there was "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes."
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American finds within himself an impulse for wildness and brutality, saying of war: "You will finally understand that this is human nature. Not sitting in comfortable seats with cigarettes and whiskey, evening newspapers or a good book and pretending that this mask represents civilization and that there is no barbarian behind the starchy self inside. "
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon, and no one will even notice, let alone grieve.
"When you finally accept the sacrifice, you would at least expect it to happen in front of a grateful audience," he writes.
Instead, he feels like a "convict whom he secretly hangs. "
Other remarks concern the departure of old Europe and the emergence of new horrors.
"The conflict has become increasingly economic competition and competition," writes Mr Englund, "a war between factories."
