After this summer's tragedy, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
"We realized that getting them isn't really that hard," says Jamie Bartlett, the leading author of a recent British research team report on European digital populism.
The supply of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, says Bartlett, that it was enough for scientists to simply use the ad on the site to determine with absolute precision the wanted demographic group - something that marketing workers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team across Europe found half a million fans of right-wing groups who focused on them and sent out ads, but instead of inviting them into a new group or offering them some diet products, they called on them to fill out a questionnaire that raised questions about their level of education, their relation to violence and optimism in relation to their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without even having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are generally young men who are enraged by the increasing level of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with off-line activism are more sensible, democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind the computer screen."
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, medical scientists and political researchers use this site to study everything, ranging from health problems to social trends hiding with updates of states, contributions to walls and pressed "I like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them will provide three different data on average, which makes this social network literally "information supernova" that is behind the development of many new researches. The number of academic works in whose name the word Facebook is found has risen to almost 800% compared to the state five years ago.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to harass them on the street.
"It used to be that when you wanted to conduct a survey among the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to a side where they'd never let you go," says Bartlett.
"This is all on Facebook - you're just going straight to them."
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a socio-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who discussed their drunken performances on Facebook were much more at risk of the problem of alcoholism than students who were silent on this subject.
Moreno suggests that students monitor the site and offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
"The problem cannot be solved if you cannot diagnose it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr Moreno and director of the Centre for Health, Behavior and Development of Children at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle.
"We've found a way to identify endangered children that we otherwise wouldn't have had a chance to discover."
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The website's information team has produced statistics on the relationship status context and Valentine's Day, the 2010 election participation and the national satisfaction coefficient (mainly using the information they had access to - Internet freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available to research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site is being watched whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site needs to be provided with personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data off-line. On-line data, however, are accessible to everyone.
"I don't think most users even thought that scientists could look into their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist in London Knowledge Lab, a study from 2006, which he conducted using his students' public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, they felt that information was between them and their friends."
Subsequently, it is also to consider the issue of methodology.
Even in off-line research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There is no way to verify on Facebook how much information on the profile and posts on the wall is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely differentiated things," Selwyn explains.
That is why Selwin, who spent years researching new technologies, thinks that the pencil and notebook remain the best possible tool to use in research.
