7 lessons from a lost conversation with Steve Jobs in a movie going to the movies this week
Once Steve Jobs died on October 5, people who compared him to Henry Ford began to appear and elected him his genius as the Greatest Modern Inventor.
At the recently rediscovered Jobs interview, which was dusted for a special film that is heading for the cinema this week, the fact will be for all Apple fans that his creative mind perfectly understood the business processes and working flows behind his products.
He was an amazing designer, dreamer, and self-appointed member of the hippie movement, but also a pedantic organizer and a person who matched every detail - he believed that many entrepreneurs suffered "the idea that 90 percent of their work was really great... [but] between an excellent idea and an excellent result there is still a long way to work."
In 1995, Bob Cringely worked on a TV show called Triumph of Computer Fools, which dealt with the dawn of personal computers. During the filming, a unique, more than an hour-long interview took place.
By that time, it had been ten years since Jobs was forced to leave Apple, and he was busy with his new computer company NeXT, and he eagerly looked at the general public's acceptance of the Internet.
Only a short part of the entire Cringely interview was used on the TV show and the original copies of the interviews were said to have been lost during transport.
Shortly after Jobs' death, however, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
This material, slightly edited, forms the basis of a 68-minute film by Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which goes to selected cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
Jobs is surprisingly enthusiastic about discussing his technological philosophy and business strategies to someone who is famous for his dislike to give longer talks.
And he also turns out to be a very thoughtful man.
Four times during the interview, a longer pause will occur between the question and the answer - 10 to 15 seconds of thinking, when it is seen how Jobs thinks perfectly to be as accurate and accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, when he is impatient about Cringely's questions and drives him to get to more important problems and topics.
The interview was recorded before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, and there are frighteningly prophetic ideas in it when Jobs evaluates what other companies do well and wrong, offering his own vision of the future in the field of computer technology.
It's one thing to read the postmortem assessments of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about Jobs, who we see here as a eager dreamer in the bloom of his genius.
He has his own vision of what things might and should look like.
It did not take long, and after he had expressed his thoughts, he also began putting them into practice.
A quick sum of seven scenes from the Lost Interview, which is definitely worth noting:
How he learned to run a business:
"During years of business, I always asked, "Why are you doing this?" and the answer was always the same: "Well, that's just how it's done."
No one knows why they do what they do, never think about business matters in depth.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues by describing his efforts to simplify accounts in Apple.
He was completely confused by the way the costs were recorded - they often began with the inscription "standard costs," their amount could only be imagined. At that moment he decided to go his own way - he developed an automatic tool that guaranteed that they could determine commercial costs within a short time.
How he performed the pope's mischief:
Jobs remembers the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that enabled people to effectively hack into the phone company and call anywhere in the world free of charge.
A number of things have been written about the device in the past, but Jobs' enthusiasm for describing the Blue Box as an instrument of power is literally contagious.
It tells how they tested the device with Wozniak using a paid phone and during the call they were transferred from one AT&T network to another while using as many satellites as possible.
"At least half a dozen times we've gotten in and around the world, so when we yelled something into a pay phone, it sounded a minute later from the other phone at the door," Jobs laughs.
"We were young, and we found that we could build ourselves a thing capable of managing infrastructure for billions of dollars around the world."
The two of us made a little thing that could control a much bigger giant - it was an incredible experience, and I don't think Apple would ever have come up without it.
Jobs continues to describe a joke that he and Wozniak almost made to the end. Through the Blue Box in the middle of the night, they called the Vatican and asked if they could speak to the Pope, impersonating Henry Kissinger as best they could.
Gradually, members of the Catholic Church were called on to speak with an American diplomat in the middle of the night, and only just before the pope himself woke up to the phone, the couple blew up and laid down the earpiece.
How he fell in love with technology (and telephoned Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 and he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he found Bill Hewlett's phone book number and called him.
Not long after their 20-minute interview, Jobs had already secured a summer brigade at Hewlett-Packard.
"I was incredibly influenced, and it was the only company I had known at the time, and it shaped my view of what such a company was and how it should treat its employees."
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the corporate research lab in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
He was as big as a suitcase, he had a CRT monitor, and I fell in love with him instantly.
As a teenager, I went higher and higher in HP, hanging around the computer and started writing programs for him.
How innovation invents:
In several places, Jobs discusses how he invents new products on the run.
In the early days of his career, when he went out to sell a few printed circuit boards, a customer asked him to put together an entire computer for him.
At his disposal he had only 30 paid days during which he had to invent, assembled and delivered the finished equipment.
Later, when he was at Apple, he recalls the problems they faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember how wildly we argued... shouting at me that it would take five years [to assemble a mouse that would cost $300] when I got tired of it, I went out and found a designer."
Ninety days later, we were able to produce a perfectly reliable mouse for $15.
How big companies run out of breath:
Long before he led Apple's resurrection, Jobs foresaw that many industrial leaders would waver in their vision and lose their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you do better photocopiers or printers, so what's next?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so society can no longer be more successful.
At that point, sales and marketing are already in control, so companies are run by people who are in charge of this, while people in charge of their own products are out of the decision-making process.
The technological genius that led society to its unshakable position is now replaced by people who have no idea of good or bad products - skill and technical knowledge are essential.
That's exactly what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could literally own the entire computer industry.
Could have been ten times the size of it, could have been Microsoft of the '90s...
But instead of winning, they lost.
As he takes innovation as a form of art:
"There is still a long journey and a lot of work between excellent ideas and excellent resulting products... and as the great idea develops, it also changes and grows."
During that time, you'll learn a lot about him.
You have to come to a whole series of compromises - you just don't make certain things happen with electrons, glass, robots or factories.
You have to keep in mind 5,000 things - different concepts - and put them together...
Finally, taste matters - you try to think of the best things that mankind has ever created, and in some ways you try to project them into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I've never been ashamed of stealing the best ideas.
Macintosh was so amazing and successful because the people who worked in it were excellent musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, and by coincidence also the best computer experts in the world.
If it weren't for computers and new technologies, they would have done amazing things in completely different sectors.
