How to Recognize Lies
A glimpse of recent headlines suggests how serious and ubiquitous lies and deceptions are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain has his hands full of accusations that he sexually harassed several women - both sides claim the other one is lying.
Managers at Penn State University were accused of perjury when they tried to hide records that a retired football coach sexually assaulted a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling US President Barrack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
The lie has been able to destroy the entire career and cloud the stability of many countries.
The New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself when he published information that was immediately refuted by undisputable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was accused of using his campaign funds to try to hide his illegitimate affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus that flew by Bill Clinton when he lied during his second period in office about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
It's all crawling with stories about cheating at school and college.
There are cases where teachers themselves give their students test answers just to look good in their own opinions.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and fraud are acceptable.
How many scams are we dealing with?
Studies show that in one day you'll lie somewhere between 10 and 200 cases.
Let us assume that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first ten minutes of their first encounter.
Determining lies, or "recognition of lies, " is an essential skill that everyone should acquire, for personal or professional reasons.
However, it is not a social game that is similar, say, to Charade, when a person shouts out: "I have you." The recognition of deception is a serious sector of science working with scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities during detailed research projects, especially in psychology and philosophy.
One of the research results is that most of the old myths about lies have been refuted.
Liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're sneaking around, stuttering, blushing or sewing.
However, do not conclude that it is somehow difficult to spot and expose a liar.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from a sentence building, small facial expressions, a way of creating questions and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from an extensive and emerging lie recognition sector, and it is clear that detection of deception is a modern skill that can be easily learned and can help you greatly in today's difficult world - especially if your duties include hiring, organising interviews, negotiating or conducting people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them down guard, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men utter more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more lies "focused on others" - mostly to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than free people (all the lies they say are usually "infamous").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
It's called early observation.
Thanks to him, he'll have a later finding out what to compare with.
Notice the posture of the subject, his laughter, his voice work.
You should know if someone is always taping their feet so that you don't wrongly accuse him of lying just because he starts taping his feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to determine the clumps of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But consider it merely as a warning signal, not as evidence of a lie.
Lying people can stop moving the upper half of their body, trying to remember their imaginary story, they can turn the boot tips to the door, lean to the exit, significantly change the posture, or show "relax after the interview" - an overly relaxing breath and a change of position when the confession behind them is difficult.
Interviewers often give a false signal that the interview is over just to see what relief will look like after the interview.
Also feel the language of the subject.
Famous is the story of how Scott Peterson once misjudged himself and used past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, which ran a nationwide search for her body.
Deceiving individuals can also express themselves with measure: "I had no sexual relationship with the Miss Lewinsky... or they will repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal characters are very tiny.
Someone can use a lot of "leathering language" when they answer the difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... from what I know... from my best knowledge."
In such an answer, we will not learn much of the facts, and it is often another warning signal.
There is no magic to reveal every lie, but it is possible to acquire skills that can help you track a lie.
With these skills, a person will have a better chance of not falling for a liar and a crook in his personal and professional life.
