The climate has slowed the economy
During the first year of the reign of Mario López Valdez, unemployment and unreliableness increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment fell, and the economy with them too.
This is the first year of the reign of Mario López Valdez, which is called the government of change. This government has brought with it great expectations as regards economic progress, however, due to adverse climate conditions at the beginning of the year no growth was recorded and even the main economic development indicators have fallen.
Low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, reduced the potential for growth in the state economy, caused a 3.6% reduction in economic activity in the first semester of this year, a historical decline of 31,16% in agriculture, which affected the dynamics of other economic sectors as well.
According to the damage report issued by the Mexican Council on Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded at 582 835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78,03% were completely destroyed and the remaining 21,07% were found partial damage.
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the state's unemployment rate increased during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa were not employed, representing an unemployment rate of 4,53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28% and between July and August average unemployment continued to increase and reached 6,19%, which represents approximately 74 000 unemployed.
Less liquidity
According to Gerard López Cervantes, the Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on steps taken at public policy level.
"We are witnessing rising unemployment, which is linked to various factors, including loss of liquidity on the market due to the limitations of resources due to legislation approved by Congress in the fight against money laundering. It is not easy for people who illegally seize dollars to earn, invest or use them," he stressed.
Stopping migration
López Cervantes said that the demographic factor is also involved in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people who go abroad to work in the United States has decreased, both because of difficult entry and because even if these people get abroad, it is difficult for them to get a job. People therefore stay and demand work from our state, and so unemployment is growing," he said.
Uncertainty
The labour market analysis in Sinaloa is also worsening because of the growing unreliableness prevailing in the field of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the employed people in the state work without paying social security benefits.
Other features of the labour market, such as low salaries, are added to unemployment and unreliableness. In this administrative territory, the lowest salaries from all over the country, as reported by the registers of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Labour Secretariat and social planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was by September 5,352 pesetas, far below the national average of 7,375 pesetas.
Shortening of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, the most significant decline in foreign direct investment over the last 10 years was also recorded in 2011. According to the Ministry of Finance, direct foreign investment amounted to $630 697 in the period from January to June, representing a decrease of 87.74% compared to $5 143 312 in the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government lists investments amounting to 17 280 million pesetas per year, which were mainly directed to companies in the field of services.
Debt
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the government of that state asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million pesos. By November no profits were recorded from debt, namely in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government, Mario López Valdés, pointed out a lack of government leadership.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011, there was no reconciliation of the will of individual sectors, including the government of the state itself.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa was really small during this year. We need to work intensively to get back the land we lost this year. In 2012 we must double our efforts, the harmonisation of all of us's efforts and especially the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better" he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said that events such as freezing at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and reduced its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowdown in the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore the dynamics that would enable us to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services.
Re-defining the mission
According to Theodore Salazar Uriarte, president of the Intermediary Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, it is necessary to push the state into more dynamic productive activities.
"We generally observe that it is working. We believe that a long-term plan needs to be drawn up in which the objectives and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resources Sinaloa has is mobilised" he said.
The Work Before Us
President Coparmex stressed the importance of identifying a vision of the future that would better manage the government's efforts.
