It's surprising when a movement comes from a group of friends, it doesn't happen very often.
From time to time, there will be a group in the city, but it is far less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We're proud of it, and it's an honor to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we play with some of them.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored that we can be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stay together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think, first of all, we're all lucky that we're still in this world, and second, the fact that we're constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends, and thanks to this, we have managed to open up musical paths that leave everyone sufficient freedom to experiment on their own.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other's music, and I think it couldn't be better.
Your relationship to the word fame was not easy. However, thanks to your success you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it was gradually getting easier to find a balance.
We try not to tour too much because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you remind yourself that you have to respect the music and what you gave her, you can't let yourself get carried away by being famous rock stars, and neither of us ever really cared.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs, and in the beginning it was something spectacular.
We were a band for three years, and we never released any album until after Andy died (Andrew Woods).
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that even today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at pictures, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed with him. It was always a pleasure working with him, laughing, talking about music or football and much more.
She was an incredible person, and we miss her so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be assigned to launch a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as the opening act?
Yes, production sent us videos with several designs and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are curious about what Las Robertas will offer live and must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words of Yellow Ledbetter in person?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He's singing it, and I think he's adding the first thing that comes to mind.
Who's affecting you as a bass player?
A lot of people.
My first thought is Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all night about bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge even though it's no longer fashionable?
I think we've all always felt easy to separate from the word grunge.
When you say grunge, I imagine groups that I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that were created at the same time, and if music is valid today, it's something great because it's music that's worth listening to and groups like Mudhoney are playing better music than ever.
At the beginning your music had a slightly grim character and now it is more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting, because I feel like there are a few songs in the new album that are lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe, which are considered very bleak, although they may sound positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're deep dark songs.
I think that when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or your boyfriend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent this to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make bleak music.
