Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jacome presented details about the accident in which the secretary of the governor, Francisco Blake, died, and seven others.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) informed that the results of the investigation of the accident in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and the other seven persons died show that the helicopter landed directly on the terrain with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt forced landing.
At the press conference Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary for Communication and Transport, said that prior to the start of the aircraft the pilot stated that climate conditions allow the flight.
"Parts that appear suggest that the unit has come into contact several times with the terrain, the wings have been tangled into the branches of trees 25 meters from where the unit has lost its hull."
He also informed that the unit was intended for 19 people, therefore it met all requirements for the transport of personnel.
In addition, he stated that no components were found on the ground following an investigation conducted in the field of impact.
"In the search it was found that parts of the aircraft were not located in another place, so the plane crashed into the mainland as a whole.
"The helicopter was intended for 19 people, meeting all requirements for the transport of persons.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of between seven and thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment it is most important to get the results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Managing Director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, stated that at the moment of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was moving at a cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that at the time of the accident it was a normal flight operation," he said.
At a press conference, Deputy SCT Pérez Jácome listed six basic points of investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was implemented according to visual flight rules, which means that the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
The AICM reports indicate adequate conditions at the start, according to which the aircraft progresses towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the clouds the crew searched for a lower area and greater visibility up to the valley of Cuernavaca.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of impact and the last recording of the helicopter from the radar are consistent, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the trajectory of the flight before the impact.
Dispersion of aircraft residue in restricted territory:
The information currently available allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a flat trajectory and from the side.
The sketch of the dispersal of the remains of the aircraft indicates that the helicopter was solid at the time of impact on the mainland.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence at the scene of the accident to indicate that there was an explosion or a fire.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During field work, the aircraft remains were found at a height of up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain slopes, the slopes go from seven to 30 degrees.
The photos show images where the route was likely to disintegrate along the route.
Information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter could have made contact with the ground in several places.
After a careful search into the vicinity of the accident, in a territory that is larger than the territory of the setting, no helicopter remains were found, which strengthens the assumption that the impact occurred in a state where the helicopter was still intact.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance started research into a gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research in order to discover the gene responsible for obesity of children and adolescents. Research is carried out with the support of experts from the Institute of IPN
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to detect a gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research entitled "Genetics of Obesity in Children and Youths" will allow for results related to overweight.
In a report by the head of the Biochemistry Research Unit of the National Medical Center, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team was established composed of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers.
This team is based on the support of specialists and students of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
People can also participate in research by the general public with or without permissions. People can come to the participating sports centers of the IMSS in Valle de México, where every Saturday at 8 o'clock will be tested by teenagers.
He stressed that research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexican State) and since 8 October this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (East Mexican State).
Once the data are obtained from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue at the Sports Centre of Independence (South of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (North of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics as regards the development of obesity, and to track down risk factors for Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Day of Diabetes, which is celebrated on 14 November, the aim is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants take anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin, and genes are studied (see genes involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects health care concerns over the alarming increase in child weight.
'The medical surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that only six years later, the boys had increased obesity by 77% and 47% in girls.
He stated that one reason for finding indicators is the belief that the population of the country is different from other populations by its genetic history.
He informed that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the general genetics of obesity are commonly explained as an inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they will receive an overall assessment of the condition of children, thus establishing whether they exhibit any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of wrinkles of dark color (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the probability that the individual would suffer from metabolic problems and pre-sugar states.
The information is so far confidential, the doctors transmit it to their parents in writing and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make in order to avoid disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary way of life, meaning a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of television all day, and using means of transport instead of walking at short distances.
Overweight also causes a large calorie intake, i.e. a larger consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and a genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in Asphalt of the UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, creates modified asphalts with polymers and thus creates a mixture with better functionality, independent of climate conditions and temperature
If pavement was properly cared for, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each period of rain in the Metropolitan region of Valle de México, warned Rafael Herrera Najera, a scientist from the Chemical Faculty (FQ) of UNAM, who also added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavement were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or it would even be possible to completely remove them.
In his lecture, the technological cause of potholes, which he gave within the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his guidance was developing modified asphalt with polymers, thereby producing a mixture with similar characteristics to asphalt, but also greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing pothole formation.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a large molecular mass called asphalten, and others with a low molecular mass called mortars. Together they provide asphalt with a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic character of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost firm, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, the expert warned about chemical engineering.
A scientist at the Chemical Faculty observed that most streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, three of which last are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers is the asphalt insert, made of small stones in tarmac and then compressed.
He pointed out that every stone that makes up an insert is covered with asphalt.
During the passage of cars or when creating pressure, it is possible for the forces in the pavement to decompose well.
If it was modified asphalt, it would decompose even better, it considers a chemical engineer.
He added that the last layer called a cloak, consisting of fine stones, i.e. sand also embedded in asphalt, would be placed on the asphalt insert.
As this layer will come into contact with the rims of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt liner and ensure road friction.
As a part of the tiling, the mantle must be of sufficient thickness and be careful of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to be remembered. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt liner.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads inside and it is hard to get out, it causes the softening of all layers of pavement and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that during the pothole formation, the film will be damaged first and then damage the asphalt liner. However, the damage does not occur in one moment, but it is a slow process that should stop at the first signs by using appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor in the formation of potholes, and therefore the thickness of each single layer of pavement must correspond to the load of vehicles and it must be ensured that this load does not exceed.
