entering the golden rule on a balanced budget into the Constitution
On Tuesday, the government of a large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided to include the "golden rule" of budgetary policy in the Constitution in order to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid any reduction in the assessment of Austria by credit rating agencies (AA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the end of a ministerial meeting in a situation where Austrian public debt, with its 74.6% high above the criterion of a maximum of 60% laid down by the Maastricht Agreement, is much lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency had been reduced by just one single degree from AAA to AA+, we would have had to pay three billion more euros each year on interest," argued Vice Chancellor and Secretary of State, Christian Democrat Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus follows the request of the Eurozone Summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where the Heads of State and Government strongly asked that a reduction in the public deficit and a balance of public accounts be entered in the Constitution or into the law of the same value by the end of 2012.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian Government is approaching the "German model," Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule."
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to fall by 0,75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and from 2017 onwards the federal state's public structural deficit will not be allowed to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while the federal countries, as well as the municipalities, will have to have a balanced budget.
The aim is to bring public debt below the 60% criterion laid down by the Maastricht Treaty in the 2020/21 horizon.
