Nord Stream, the new entry port of Russian gas to Europe
Nord Stream's long-distance pipeline connecting directly Eastern Europe to Russia and led along the Baltic Sea began to work.
It must deliver a gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, among them four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday's Nord Stream inauguration, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
In symbolic terms, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned the control around the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow every year to Western Europe by the first pipeline of 1 224 km connecting the region of St Petersburg to the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will allow a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be delivered, which is the quantity that equals the entire French consumption.
And it is already recalled the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom the early completion of this huge construction has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being run by a third State (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing a little bit of power: the possibility of pushing Russia by threatening to shut down its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed it most strongly when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact" with an appeal to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means that it is politically sensitive.
With its support for this Russian project, Western Europe gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project created cracks between Europeans from the east and west.
Russia barely succeeded five years ago in promoting its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and wealthy Western states with high gas consumption, whose bearings are coming to an end.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us" confirmed François Fillon at the opening ceremony of this pipeline and demonstrated at what point large gas contracts of things are both political and economic.
This all explains the broad smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
Undersea pipes are made of steel fitted with a concrete casing to protect them from the anchors of sea vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction it was necessary to avoid the minefields from World War II.
"For safety reasons, almost a hundred had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, Nord Stream's spokesman.
It was also necessary to increase measures to protect fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not broken anywhere over its entire length by valves or maintenance stations.
One inspection platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project manager rejected it when the Swedes were little eager to see a Russian state society settling permanently off their coast.
"In case of failure we stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute," explains Jens Müller.
In case of leakage gas contained in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, for the welds were designed to cause leakage once every 100,000 years.
Checking the state of the gas pipeline from the outside is carried out by an underwater ship-drawn robot, while the inside of the gas pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 metre is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
At the end of the three-day journey, at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts.
The long-distance pipeline has been designed to work for 50 years without the slightest need for repair.
Circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at start and 100 bar at finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom, holding a 51% stake, remains the lead.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company has its registered office in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased all its gas transport capacity to this company for five years by a contract that can be renewed.
"Gazprom will have a profit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of really transported gas," explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should reach EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, investment costs rose to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be refunded, because Gazprom is the only one taking the risk.
The pipeline exits from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on the sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves 5 feet high form the exit gate of the gas.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
