Why is the proportion of unemployed handicapped workers so high?
Around 19% of handicapped people are looking for work.
Today, the 15th week for the employment of handicapped people opens.
Despite the Voluntarist public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed handicapped persons is still twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% versus 9% for the whole population.
Is it depressing?
"No, Eric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt Association, who organizes the Week for the employment of handicapped people."
"The steps achieved in 15 years are remarkable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate wasn't twice but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It should be said that there are numerous obstacles for unemployed disabled people before their entry into work.
Elderly: 37% has more than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low qualification: 80% of them have no graduation, and only 10,000 of the 2.3 million college students are handicapped.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for handicapped versus 38% on average.
In short, these are criteria which make it particularly difficult to return to work and which represent the "core problem", according to Christian Grapin, the CEO of the Treplin Association, which was established in 1992 to help businesses receive handicapped workers.
So much for objective brakes.
There are unspoken ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slow.
A study by the IMS-Entrepredre pour la Cité association in April found that the surveyed managers had a "weak level of knowledge of handicapped persons" with an "exaggeration of persons in wheelchairs and mental or mental deficiencies."
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the objective of employing 6% of handicapped workers laid down in the 1987 Law.
The last known figures, which come from 2008, indicate a state equal to 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, responsible for charging businesses that do not comply with this law.
The proof is that the number of companies being fined, as well as the sums paid, which fell between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euro), are guilty.
"The 2005 Law, which increased the contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also demonstrates real awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of enterprises with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
